"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/427086","Department for Education","false","2015-11-17","<p>The Department for Education does not have a full breakdown of revenue spent on staff salaries for proposed free school projects.</p><br /><p>The total pre-opening expenditure for free school projects is published on GOV.UK:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/revenue-expenditure-for-free-schools" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/revenue-expenditure-for-free-schools</a></p><br /><p>We will shortly update this information to include projects that opened or were withdrawn or cancelled up to September 2015.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","15417","2015-11-17T16:14:47.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/427086/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/427086/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/427086/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-11-09","Free Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will list all the free school projects that have been withdrawn or cancelled to date; and what the cost to the public purse was of the withdrawal or cancellation of each such project.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","15557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/427087","Department for Education","false","2015-11-19","<p>Officials in the Department for Education are in contact with their counterparts in the devolved administrations on a range of subjects, such as cross-border checks on those working in childcare and participation in international studies, including the OECD’s Programme for International Student Assessment.</p><br /><p>To provide a complete breakdown of every meeting over the past three years would exceed the disproportionate cost threshold.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2015-11-19T15:57:17.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/427087/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/427087/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/427087/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-11-09","Education: Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when her officials met with their counterparts in the devolved administrations in the last three years; and what the subjects for discussion or agreement were at each of those meetings.","false","Biography information for Danny Kinahan","South Antrim","Danny Kinahan","15521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/427088","Department for Education","false","2015-11-19","<p>Area reviews of post-16 education and training institutions are predominantly focused on general further education and sixth form colleges in order to ensure that there are high quality, financially resilient colleges across the country. Schools with sixth forms can opt in to a review, if they wish to do so, and if they have the agreement of the review’s local steering group.</p><br /><p>Each review will conduct a comprehensive analysis of the current post-16 provision in the area which will include the offer made by schools with sixth forms. Regional Schools Commissioners and local authorities will sit on local area review steering groups. These groups will identify issues with school sixth form provision, including provision by academy sixth forms, free school sixth forms, and University Technical Colleges, and feed these issues into the reviews. We expect Regional Schools Commissioners and local authorities to take account of the analysis from area reviews in any decisions they make about future provision.</p><br /><p>The reviews are aimed at delivering a skills system that meets the economic and educational needs of areas whilst also ensuring the long term sustainability of colleges to support productivity. Early evidence from the pilot reviews indicates that there is also potential for the reviews to secure efficiency savings.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","15486","2015-11-19T12:22:01.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/427088/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/427088/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/427088/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-11-09","Sixth Form Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, why school and academy sixth forms have not been included in recommendations arising out of reviews of post-16 education and training; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","15482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/427089","Department for Education","false","2015-11-19","<p>Area reviews of post-16 education and training institutions are predominantly focused on general further education and sixth form colleges in order to ensure that there are high quality, financially resilient colleges across the country. Schools with sixth forms can opt in to a review, if they wish to do so, and if they have the agreement of the review’s local steering group.</p><br /><p>Each review will conduct a comprehensive analysis of the current post-16 provision in the area which will include the offer made by schools with sixth forms. Regional Schools Commissioners and local authorities will sit on local area review steering groups. These groups will identify issues with school sixth form provision, including provision by academy sixth forms, free school sixth forms, and University Technical Colleges, and feed these issues into the reviews. We expect Regional Schools Commissioners and local authorities to take account of the analysis from area reviews in any decisions they make about future provision.</p><br /><p>The reviews are aimed at delivering a skills system that meets the economic and educational needs of areas whilst also ensuring the long term sustainability of colleges to support productivity. Early evidence from the pilot reviews indicates that there is also potential for the reviews to secure efficiency savings.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","15482","2015-11-19T12:22:01.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/427089/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/427089/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/427089/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-11-09","Further Education and Sixth Form Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to her Department's publication, Reviewing post-16 education and training institutions, of 20 July